Definition 6. Each object of the category $\mathbf{CTop}$ of partially covered topological spaces is a triple $(X,\mathcal{T},\mathcal{U})$, where $(X,\mathcal{T})$ is a topological space and $\mathcal{U}\subseteq\mathcal{T}$ is a collection2$\mathcal{U}$ may not be a cover of $X$, but covers a subspace. This is important for Definition 12. of open sets. Each morphism $f:(X,\mathcal{T}_{X},\mathcal{V})\to(X,\mathcal{T}_{Y},\mathcal{U})$ of $\mathbf{CTop}$ is a continuous map $f:(X,\mathcal{T}_{X})\to(Y,\mathcal{T}_{Y})$ such that each $V\in\mathcal{V}$ is a subset of $f^{-1}(U)$ for some $U\in\mathcal{U}$.
Definition 10. (compare the definition in [1]) For each pair of objects $(X,\mathcal{T},{\bf V})$, $(Y,\mathcal{S},{\bf U})$ in $\mathbf{SCTop}$, the function $D((X,\mathcal{T},{\bf V}),(Y,\mathcal{S},{\bf U}))=\inf\{\epsilon:\text{there % is an }\epsilon\text{-interleaving }(X,\mathcal{T},{\bf V})\to(Y,\mathcal{S},{% \bf U})\}$ is a pseudometric, called the interleaving distance. The same definition works for objects in $\mathbf{PMod}$, mutatis mutandis.
Definition 4. Each object of the category $\mathbf{ShvA}$ of sheaf assignments consists of a sheaf $\mathcal{S}$ and assignment $a\in\prod_{U\text{ open}}\mathcal{S}(U)$ to that sheaf. In this category, morphisms consist of sheaf morphisms that are compatible with the assignment, in the following way. Suppose that $a$ is an assignment to a sheaf $\mathcal{S}$ on a space $X$ and $b$ is an assignment to a sheaf $\mathcal{R}$ on a space $Y$. A sheaf morphism $m:\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{R}$ along a continuous map $f:X\to Y$ is morphism $(\mathcal{S},a)\to(\mathcal{R},b)$ in $\mathbf{ShvA}$ if for each open $U\subseteq Y$, the component map $m_{U}:\mathcal{S}(f^{-1}(U))\to\mathcal{R}(U)$ satisfies $m_{U}(a(f^{-1}(U)))=b(U).$ We will also make use of the following subcategories: • The subcategory $\mathbf{ShvFPA}$ of assignments to sheaves of pseudometric spaces, • The subcategory $\mathbf{ShvA}(X,\mathcal{T})$ of assignments to sheaves on a fixed base space, • The subcategory $\mathbf{ShvPA}(X,\mathcal{T})$ of assignments to sheaves of pseudometric spaces on a fixed base space, and • The subcategory $\mathbf{ShvFPA}(X,\mathcal{T})$ of assignments to sheaves of pseudometric spaces on a finite fixed base space.
Definition 8. (equivalent to [2, Def. 2.12]) The category $\mathbf{PMod}$ of shifted persistence modules has persistence modules as its objects and persistence module morphisms shifted by order preserving functions as its morphisms. Each object of $\mathbf{PMod}$ is a functor from the poset category $(\mathbb{R},\leq)$ to the category of vector spaces. Explicitly, each object is a choice of a vector space ${\bf E}(t)$ for each real number $t$ and a choice of linear map $f_{{\bf E},t\leq t^{\prime}}:E(t)\to E(t^{\prime})$ for each $t\leq t^{\prime}$ such that $f_{{\bf E},t\leq t^{\prime\prime}}=f_{{\bf E},t^{\prime}\leq t^{\prime\prime}}% \circ f_{{\bf E},t\leq t^{\prime}}$ and $f_{{\bf E},t\leq t}=\textrm{id }_{{\bf E}(t)}.$ Each morphism ${\bf E}\to{\bf F}$ of $\mathbf{PMod}$ is an order preserving map $\phi:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$ and a choice of a set of maps $g_{t}:{\bf E}(\inf\phi^{-1}(t))\to{\bf F}(t)$ such that the following diagram commutes $\xymatrix{{\bf E}(\inf\phi^{-1}(t))\ar[rrr]^{f_{{\bf E},\inf\phi^{-1}(t)\leq% \inf\phi^{-1}(t^{\prime})}}\ar[d]_{g_{t}}&&&{\bf E}(\inf\phi^{-1}(t^{\prime}))% \ar[d]^{g_{t}^{\prime}}\\ {\bf F}(t)\ar[rrr]_{f_{{\bf F},t\leq t^{\prime}}}&&&{\bf F}(t^{\prime})\\ }$ for all $t\leq t^{\prime}$.
Definition 1. [6]. For a sheaf $\mathcal{S}$ on a topological space $(X,\mathcal{T})$, an assignment is an element $a\in\prod_{U\in\mathcal{T}}\mathcal{S}(U)$. When for each open $U\in\mathcal{T}$, $\mathcal{S}(U)$ is a pseudometric space with pseudometric $d_{U}$, the set of assignments has the assignment pseudometric given by $D(a,b)=\sup_{U\in\mathcal{T}}d_{U}\left(a(U),b(U)\right).$ For an assignment $a$ to a sheaf $\mathcal{S}$, each value $d_{U}\left(\left(\mathcal{S}(U\subseteq V)\right)a(V),a(U)\right)$ where $U\subseteq V\in\mathcal{T}$, is called a critical threshold. The consistency radius given by $c_{\mathcal{S}}(a)=\sup_{U\subseteq V\in\mathcal{T}}d_{U}\left(\left(\mathcal{% S}(U\subseteq V)\right)a(V),a(U)\right),$ is the supremum of all critical thresholds.
Definition 11. If $\mathcal{U}\subseteq\mathcal{T}$ is a collection of open sets for a topological space $(X,\mathcal{T})$ and $\mathcal{S}$ is a sheaf of pseudometrics on $(X,\mathcal{T})$, then an assignment supported on $\mathcal{U}$ is an element of $\prod_{U\in\mathcal{U}}\mathcal{S}(U)$. The consistency radius of an assignment $a$ supported on $\mathcal{U}$ is written $c_{\mathcal{S}}(a,\mathcal{U})$, and is the infimum of all consistency radii of assignments $b$ that restrict to $a$, namely $c_{\mathcal{S}}(a,\mathcal{U})=\inf\left\{c_{\mathcal{S}}(b):b\in\prod_{V\in% \mathcal{T}}\mathcal{S}(V)\text{ such that }b(U)=a(U)\text{ whenever }U\in% \mathcal{U}\right\}.$ We say that each such assignment $b$ extends $a$.
Definition 15. For an assignment $a$ supported on the stars of a sheaf $\mathcal{S}$ of pseudometric spaces on an Alexandrov space $X$, the star consistency radius on an open subset $U\subseteq X$ is given by $\displaystyle c^{*}_{\mathcal{S}}(a,U)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\max\{\sup_{y\in U,}\sup_{x\in\textrm{star }y}d_{\textrm{star }x}% \left(\left(\mathcal{S}(\textrm{star }x\subseteq\textrm{star }y)\right)a(% \textrm{star }y),a(\textrm{star }x)\right),$ $\displaystyle\sup_{y\in U,}\sup_{x\in U,}\sup_{z\in\textrm{star }x\cap\textrm{% star }y}\frac{1}{2}d_{\textrm{star }z}\left(\left(\mathcal{S}(\textrm{star }z% \subseteq\textrm{star }y)\right)a(\textrm{star }y),\left(\mathcal{S}(\textrm{% star }z\subseteq\textrm{star }x)\right)a(\textrm{star }x)\right)\}$
Definition 2. The category $\mathbf{Pseud}$ is the category of pseudometric spaces, in which objects are pseudometric spaces and the morphisms are continuous maps.
Definition 7. The category of coarsening filtrations $\mathbf{SCTop}$ describes a collection of refinements of partial covers on fixed topological spaces. Each object is a triple $(X,\mathcal{T},{\bf V})$ where $(X,\mathcal{T})$ is a topological space and ${\bf V}$ is a function ${\bf V}:\mathbb{R}\to 2^{\mathcal{T}},$ for which ${\bf V}(t)$ is a collection of open sets in $(X,\mathcal{T})$ for all $t$ and ${\bf V}(t)$ refines ${\bf V}(t^{\prime})$ whenever $t\leq t^{\prime}$. If $(X,\mathcal{T},{\bf V})$ and $(Y,\mathcal{S},{\bf U})$ are objects of $\mathbf{SCTop}$, a morphism $(X,\mathcal{T},{\bf V})\to(Y,\mathcal{S},{\bf U})$ in $\mathbf{SCTop}$ consists of an order preserving function $\phi:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$ and a family of continuous functions $f_{t}:(X,\mathcal{T})\to(Y,\mathcal{S})$ such that for all $t$, ${\bf V}(s)$ refines $f_{t}^{-1}({\bf U}(t))$ for all $s\in\phi^{-1}(t)$.
Definition 13. The consistency filtration associates the coarsening filtration $\left({\bf CF}(\mathcal{S},a)\right)(t)=\mathcal{M}_{\mathcal{S},a}(t)$ to each sheaf assignment $(\mathcal{S},a)$ on a finite space.
Definition 5. Suppose that $a$ is an assignment to a sheaf $\mathcal{S}$ of pseudometric spaces on a finite space. The inconsistency $I_{\mathcal{S},a}(U)$ of an open set $U$ is $I_{\mathcal{S},a}(U)=\sum_{V_{1}\subseteq V_{2}\subseteq U}d_{V_{1}}\left((% \mathcal{S}(V_{1}\subseteq V_{2}))a(V_{2}),a(V_{1})\right).$
Definition 9. A pair of morphisms $f_{t}:(X,\mathcal{T},{\bf V})\to(Y,\mathcal{S},{\bf U})$, $g_{t}:(Y,\mathcal{S},{\bf U})\to(X,\mathcal{T},{\bf V})$ along $\phi$, $\psi$ (respectively) in $\mathbf{SCTop}$ is an $\epsilon$-interleaving if each of the following hold for all $t$: 1. $|\phi(t)-t|<\epsilon$, 2. $|\psi(t)-t|<\epsilon$, 3. ${\bf V}(\inf(\psi\circ\phi)^{-1}(t))$ refines ${\bf V}(t)$, and 4. ${\bf U}(\inf(\phi\circ\psi)^{-1}(t))$ refines ${\bf U}(t)$. An $\epsilon$-interleaving between two morphisms $f_{t}:{\bf E}\to{\bf F}$, $g_{t}:{\bf E}\to{\bf F}$ along $\phi$, $\psi$ (respectively) in $\mathbf{PMod}$ may be defined in exactly the same way.
Definition 14. An $\epsilon$-consistent partition for an assignment $a$ to a sheaf $\mathcal{S}$ of pseudometric spaces on $(X,\mathcal{T})$, consists of a partition $X=\bigsqcup X_{k}$ such that $c_{i^{*}_{k}\mathcal{S}}(i^{*}_{k}a)<\epsilon$ for every $k$.
Definition 12. Let $a$ be an assignment to a sheaf $\mathcal{S}$ of pseudometric spaces on $(X,\mathcal{T})$. A collection of open sets $\mathcal{U}$ is an $\epsilon$-consistent collection if for every $U\in\mathcal{U}$, either the consistency radius on $U$ is less than $\epsilon$ $c_{\mathcal{S}}(a,U)<\epsilon.$
Definition 4.1 For a Cartesian left additive category, a $\mathsf{D}$-sequence is a pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequence ${f_{\bullet}}$ such that for each $n\in\mathbb{N}$ the following equalities hold: [DS.1] $\langle 1,0\rangle\cdot\mathsf{D}^{n+1}[f_{\bullet}]=0_{\bullet}$; [DS.2] $\left(1\times(\pi_{0}+\pi_{1})\right)\cdot\mathsf{D}^{n+1}[f_{\bullet}]=\left(% (1\times\pi_{0})\cdot\mathsf{D}^{n+1}[f_{\bullet}]\right)+\left((1\times\pi_{1% })\cdot\mathsf{D}^{n+1}[f_{\bullet}]\right)$; [DS.3] $\ell\cdot\mathsf{D}^{n+2}[f_{\bullet}]=\mathsf{D}^{n+1}[f_{\bullet}]$ where recall $\ell=\langle 1,0\rangle\times\langle 0,1\rangle$; [DS.4] $c\cdot\mathsf{D}^{n+2}[f_{\bullet}]=\mathsf{D}^{n+2}[f_{\bullet}]$ where recall $c:=1\times\langle\pi_{1},\pi_{0}\rangle\times 1$.
Definition A.3 For a category $\mathbb{X}$ with finite products, a generalized $\mathsf{D}$-sequence, denoted by $f_{\bullet}:\left(A,(M,+_{M},0_{M})\right)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to% 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}\left(B,(N,+_{N},0_{N})\right)$ – where $A$ and $B$ are arbitrary objects of $\mathbb{X}$, while $(M,+_{M},0_{M})$ and $(N,+_{N},0_{N})$ are commutative monoids of $\mathbb{X}$ – is a generalized pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequence $f_{\bullet}:(A,M)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits}(B,N)$ such that for each $n\in\mathbb{N}$ and $k\leq n$, the following equalities hold: [GDS.$1^{\prime}$] $\langle 1_{A},0_{M}\rangle f_{1}=0$ and $\mathsf{U}\left(\tilde{\mathsf{P}}^{k}\left(\langle 1_{A},0_{M}\rangle,\langle 1% _{M},0_{M}\rangle\right)\right)f_{n+2}=0$; [GDS.$2^{\prime}$] $\mathsf{U}\left(\tilde{\mathsf{P}}^{k}\left(1_{A},+_{M}\right)\right)f_{n+1}=% \left\langle\mathsf{U}\left(\tilde{\mathsf{P}}^{k}\left(1_{A},\pi_{0}\right)% \right)f_{n+1},\mathsf{U}\left(\tilde{\mathsf{P}}^{k}\left(1_{A},\pi_{1}\right% )\right)f_{n+1}\right\rangle+_{M}$; [GDS.$3^{\prime}$] $\mathsf{U}\left(\tilde{\mathsf{P}}^{k}\left(\langle 1_{A},0_{M}\rangle,\langle 0% _{M},1_{A}\rangle\right)\right)f_{n+2}=f_{n+1}$; [GDS.$4^{\prime}$] $cf_{2}=f_{2}$ and $\mathsf{U}\left(\tilde{\mathsf{P}}^{k}\left(c,c\right)\right)f_{n+3}=f_{n+3}$.
Definition 3.3 For a pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequence $f_{\bullet}:A\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits}B$ we define the following two pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequences: (i) Its tangent pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequence $\mathsf{T}(f_{\bullet}):\mathsf{P}(A)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0% pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}\mathsf{P}(B)$ where: $\mathsf{T}(f_{\bullet})_{n}:=\xymatrixcolsep{5pc}\xymatrix{\mathsf{P}^{n+1}(A)% \ar[rr]^{-}{\langle\mathsf{P}^{n}(\pi_{0})f_{n},f_{n+1}\rangle}&&\mathsf{P}(B)}$ (ii) Its differential pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequence $\mathsf{D}[f_{\bullet}]:\mathsf{P}(A)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0% pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}B$ where $\mathsf{D}[f_{\bullet}]_{n}:=f_{n+1}$.
Definition 3.5 For a category $\mathbb{X}$ with finite products, we define its category of pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequences $\overline{\mathcal{D}}[\mathbb{X}]$ as follows: 1. Objects of $\overline{\mathcal{D}}[\mathbb{X}]$ are objects of $\mathbb{X}$; 2. Maps of $\overline{\mathcal{D}}[\mathbb{X}]$ are pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequences $f_{\bullet}:A\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits}B$; 3. The identity is the pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequence $i_{\bullet}:A\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits}A$ where for $n\geq 1$: $\begin{gathered}\displaystyle i_{n}:=\xymatrixcolsep{4.5pc}\xymatrix{\mathsf{P% }^{n}(A)\ar[r]^{-}{\pi_{1}}&\displaystyle\mathsf{P}^{n-1}(A)\ar[r]^{-}{\pi_{1}% }&\displaystyle\ldots\ar[r]^{-}{\pi_{1}}&\displaystyle\mathsf{P}(A)\ar[r]^{-}{% \pi_{1}}&\displaystyle A\end{gathered}}$ and $i_{0}:=1_{A}$. 4. Composition of pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequences $f_{\bullet}:A\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits}B$ and $g_{\bullet}:B\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits}C$ is the pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequence ${f_{\bullet}\ast g_{\bullet}:A\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}C}$ where: $\begin{gathered}\displaystyle\left(f_{\bullet}\ast g_{\bullet}\right)_{n}:=% \xymatrixcolsep{5pc}\xymatrix{\mathsf{P}^{n}(A)\ar[r]^{-}{\mathsf{T}^{n}(f_{% \bullet})_{0}}&\displaystyle\mathsf{P}^{n}(B)\ar[r]^{-}{g_{n}}&\displaystyle C% \end{gathered}}$
Definition A.1 A generalized Cartesian differential category [8, Definition 2.1] is a category $\mathbb{X}$ with finite products such that: 1) For each object $A$, there is a chosen commutative monoid $(\mathsf{L}(A),+_{A},0_{A})$, where $+_{A}:\mathsf{L}(A)\times\mathsf{L}(A)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.% 0pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}\mathsf{L}(A)\quad\quad 0_{A}:\mathsf{1}% \allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}\mathsf{L% }(A)$ and such that these choices satisfy $\mathsf{L}(\mathsf{L}(A))=\mathsf{L}(A)$ and $\mathsf{L}(A\times B)=\mathsf{L}(A)\times\mathsf{L}(B)$. 2) And $\mathbb{X}$ comes equipped with a combinator $\mathsf{D}$ on maps, which written as an inference rule gives: $\infer{\mathsf{D}[f]:A\times\mathsf{L}(A)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to % 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}\mathsf{L}(B)}{f:A\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{% \hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}B}$ such that $\mathsf{D}$ satisfies the equalities found in [8, Definition 2.1].
Definition 2.1 A left additive category [2, Definition 1.1.1] is a category such that each hom-set is a commutative monoid, with addition $+$ and zero $0$, such that composition on the left preserves the additive structure, that is $f(g+h)=fg+fh$ and $f0=0$. A map $h$ in a left additive category is additive [2] if composition on the right by $h$ preserves the additive structure, that is $(f+g)h=fh+gh$ and $0h=0$.
Definition A.2 For a category $\mathbb{X}$ with finite products, a generalized pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequence between pairs of objects $(A,M)$ and $(B,N)$, denoted $f_{\bullet}:(A,M)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits}(B,N)$, is a sequence of maps of $f_{\bullet}:=(f_{0},f_{1},\ldots)$, where $f_{0}:A\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}B$ and $f_{n+1}:\mathsf{U}\left(\tilde{\mathsf{P}}^{n}(A,M)\right)\allowbreak\mathrel{% \mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}N$ for all $n\in\mathbb{N}$.
Definition 2.4 A Cartesian differential category [2, Definition 2.1.1] is a Cartesian left additive category with a combinator $\mathsf{D}$ on maps – called the differential combaintor – which written as an inference rule gives: $\infer{\mathsf{D}[f]:A\times A\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}B}{f:A\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}B}$ such that $\mathsf{D}$ satisfies the following: [CD.1] $\mathsf{D}[f+g]=\mathsf{D}[f]+\mathsf{D}[g]$ and $\mathsf{D}[0]$; [CD.2] $\left(1\times(\pi_{0}+\pi_{1})\right)\mathsf{D}[f]=(1\times\pi_{0})\mathsf{D}[% f]+(1\times\pi_{1})\mathsf{D}[f]$ and $\langle 1,0\rangle\mathsf{D}[f]=0$; [CD.3] $\mathsf{D}[1]=\pi_{1}$ and $\mathsf{D}[\pi_{j}]=\pi_{1}\pi_{j}$ (with $j\in\{0,1\}$); [CD.4] $\mathsf{D}[\langle f,g\rangle]=\langle\mathsf{D}[f],\mathsf{D}[g]\rangle$; [CD.5] $\mathsf{D}[fg]=\langle\pi_{0}f,\mathsf{D}[f]\rangle\mathsf{D}[g]$; [CD.6] $\ell\mathsf{D}^{2}[f]=\mathsf{D}[f]$ where $\ell=\langle 1,0\rangle\times\langle 0,1\rangle$; [CD.7] $c\mathsf{D}^{2}[f]=\mathsf{D}^{2}[f]$ where $c:=1\times\langle\pi_{1},\pi_{0}\rangle\times 1$. In a Cartesian differential category, a map $f$ is said to be linear [2, Definition 2.2.1] if $\mathsf{D}[f]=\pi_{1}f$.
Definition 3.1 In a category with finite products, a pre-$\mathsf{D}$-sequence from $A$ to $B$, which we denote as $f_{\bullet}:A\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits}B$, is a sequence of maps $f_{\bullet}=(f_{0},f_{1},f_{2},\ldots)$ where $f_{n}:\mathsf{P}^{n}(A)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}B$.
Definition 4.6 Let $\mathbb{X}$ be a Cartesian left additive category. Then we denote $\mathcal{D}[\mathbb{X}]$ as the sub-Cartesian left additive category of $\overline{\mathcal{D}}[\mathbb{X}]$ of $\mathsf{D}$-sequences of $\mathbb{X}$.
Definition 2.2 A Cartesian left additive category [2, Definition 1.2.1] is a left additive category with finite products such that all projections $\pi_{i}$ are additive.
Definition 5.2. For $\mu$ a regular cardinal, we say that a category $\mathcal{K}$ is locally $\mu$-[multi/poly]presentable if it is $\mu$-accessible and has all [multi/poly]colimits. Locally [multi/poly]presentable means locally $\mu^{\prime}$-[multi/poly]presentable for some $\mu^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.4. A $\mu$-AEC $\mathbf{K}$ admits intersections if for any $N\in\mathbf{K}$ and any $A\subseteq UN$, the set $\mathbf{cl}_{\mathbf{K}}^{N}(A)=\mathbf{cl}^{N}(A):=\bigcap\{M\in\mathbf{K}% \mid M\leq_{\mathbf{K}}N,A\subseteq UM\}$ is the universe of a $\leq_{\mathbf{K}}$-substructure of $M$. In this case, we abuse notation and write $\mathbf{cl}^{N}(A)$ for this substructure as well.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a category and let $\lambda$ be a regular cardinal. (1) An object $M$ is $\lambda$-presentable if its hom-functor $\mathcal{K}(M,-):\mathcal{K}\to\operatorname{\bf Set}$ preserves $\lambda$-directed colimits. Put another way, $M$ is $\lambda$-presentable if for any morphism $f:M\to N$ with $N$ a $\lambda$-directed colimit $\langle\phi_{\alpha}:N_{\alpha}\to N\rangle$, $f$ factors essentially uniquely through one of the $N_{\alpha}$, i.e. $f=\phi_{\alpha}f_{\alpha}$ for some $f_{\alpha}:M\to N_{\alpha}$. (2) $\mathcal{K}$ is $\lambda$-accessible if it has $\lambda$-directed colimits and $\mathcal{K}$ contains a set $S$ of $\lambda$-presentable objects such that every object of $\mathcal{K}$ is a $\lambda$-directed colimit of objects in $S$. (3) $\mathcal{K}$ is accessible if it is $\lambda^{\prime}$-accessible for some regular cardinal $\lambda^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mu$ be a regular cardinal. $K$ is a $\mu$-universal class if: (1) $K$ is a class of structures in a fixed $\mu$-ary vocabulary $\tau=\tau(K)$. (2) $K$ is closed under isomorphism, unions of $\mu$-directed systems of $\tau$-substructure inclusions, and $\tau$-substructures. When $\mu=\aleph_{0}$, we omit it and just say that $K$ is a universal class.
Definition 2.3. Let $\mu$ be a regular cardinal. An abstract class $\mathbf{K}$ is a $\mu$-abstract elementary class (or $\mu$-AEC for short) if it satisfies the following three axioms: (1) Coherence: for any $M_{0},M_{1},M_{2}\in\mathbf{K}$, if $M_{0}\subseteq M_{1}\leq_{\mathbf{K}}M_{2}$ and $M_{0}\leq_{\mathbf{K}}M_{2}$, then $M_{0}\leq_{\mathbf{K}}M_{1}$. (2) Chain axioms: if $\langle M_{i}:i\in I\rangle$ is a $\mu$-directed system in $\mathbf{K}$, then: (a) $M:=\bigcup_{i\in I}M_{i}$ is in $\mathbf{K}$. (b) $M_{i}\leq_{\mathbf{K}}M$ for all $i\in I$. (c) If $M_{i}\leq_{\mathbf{K}}N$ for all $i\in I$, then $M\leq_{\mathbf{K}}N$. (3) Löwenheim-Skolem-Tarski (LST) axiom: there exists a cardinal $\lambda=\lambda^{<\mu}\geq|\tau(\mathbf{K})|+\mu$ such that for any $M\in\mathbf{K}$ and any $A\subseteq UM$, there exists $M_{0}\in\mathbf{K}$ with $M_{0}\leq_{\mathbf{K}}M$, $A\subseteq UM_{0}$, and $|UM_{0}|\leq|A|^{<\mu}+\lambda$. We write $\operatorname{LS}(\mathbf{K})$ for the least such $\lambda$.
Definition 2.6. A $\mu$-AEC $\mathbf{K}$ is pseudo-universal if it admits intersections and whenever $f,g:M\rightarrow N$ are $\mathbf{K}$-embeddings and $A\subseteq UM$ is such that $f\upharpoonright A=g\upharpoonright A$, then $f\upharpoonright\mathbf{cl}^{M}(A)=g\upharpoonright\mathbf{cl}^{M}(A)$.
Definition 5.1. For $\mu$ a regular cardinal, we say that a category $\mathcal{K}$ is locally $\mu$-presentable if it is $\mu$-accessible and has all (small) colimits. We say it is locally presentable if it is $\mu^{\prime}$-locally presentable for some $\mu^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.4. An algebra $A$ for an operad $O$ is a set $A$ equipped with an operad homomorphism $\xi:O\rightarrow taut(A)$.
Definition 2.6. Let $x:X\rightarrow\mathbb{N}$ and $y:Y\rightarrow\mathbb{N}$ be graded sets. A morphism of graded sets between them is a function $f:X\rightarrow Y$ which makes the following triangle commute: $\xymatrix{X{}{}{}{}{}{}{}{}{}{}\xy@@ix@{{\hbox{}}}}$
Definition 2.2. A homomorphism of operads $f:O\rightarrow P$ is a sequence of maps $\{f_{n}:O(n)\rightarrow P(n)\}_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$ that preserves both the identity operation and composition maps.
Definition 2.1. A nonsymmetric operad $O$ consists of a sequence of sets $\{O(n)\}_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$ whose $n$-th entry is the set of $n$-ary operations, an identity operation $\mathbbm{1}\in O(1)$, and for all $n,k_{1},k_{2},...,k_{n}\in\mathbb{N}$ a composition operation $\circ:O(n)\times\displaystyle\prod_{i=1}^{n}O(k_{i})\rightarrow O(% \displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{n}k_{i})$ such that $\theta_{0}\circ(\theta_{1}\circ(\theta_{1_{1}},...,\theta_{1_{k}}),...,\theta_% {n}\circ(\theta_{n_{1}},...,\theta_{n_{l}}))=(\theta_{0}\circ(\theta_{1},...,% \theta_{n}))\circ(\theta_{1_{1}},...,\theta_{1_{k}},...,\theta_{n_{1}},...,% \theta_{n_{l}})$ and $\theta_{0}\circ(\mathbbm{1},\mathbbm{1},...,\mathbbm{1})=\theta_{0}=\mathbbm{1% }\circ\theta_{0}$ for all $\theta_{i}\in\{O(n)\}_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$ whenever the compositions are well-defined.
Definition 2.3. The tautological operad $taut(X)$ on a set $X$ is the operad whose $n$-ary operations are $\Set(X^{n},X)$, identity operation is the identity map $\mathbbm{1}_{X}:X\rightarrow X$, and composition is given by $\circ:\Set(X^{n},X)\times\displaystyle\prod_{i=1}^{n}\Set(X^{k_{i}},X)% \rightarrow\Set(X^{n},X)\times\Set(X^{\sum_{i}k_{i}},X^{n})\rightarrow\Set(X^{% \sum_{i}k_{i}},X)$ where first we take the disjoint union of maps in the second factor, keeping the first factor fixed, and then compose the resulting two factors as set maps.
Definition 2.5. A graded set is a set $X$ equipped with a function $x:X\rightarrow\mathbb{N}$ called the arity map.
Definition 3.17. A group-groupoid $\mathbb{G}$ is called abelian if it coincide with its centre, i.e. $\mathbb{G}=Z(\mathbb{G})$.
Definition 3.29. A subgroup-groupoid $\mathbb{H}$ of a group-groupoid $\mathbb{G}$ is called characteristic in $\mathbb{G}$ if restriction defines a group-groupoid morphism $\mathcal{A}(\mathbb{G})\rightarrow\mathcal{A}(\mathbb{H})$.
Definition 3.3. [20] Let $\mathbb{G}$ be a group-groupoid and $\mathbb{N}$ a subgroupoid of $\mathbb{G}$ such that $N_{1}$ is a normal subgroup of $G_{1}$. Then $\mathbb{N}$ is called a normal subgroup-groupoid of $\mathbb{G}$ and this denoted by $\mathbb{H}\lhd\mathbb{G}$.
Definition 2.1. Let $f,g\colon\mathbb{C}\rightarrow\mathbb{D}$ be two functors. A natural transformation $\eta\colon f\Rightarrow g$ from $f$ to $g$ is a class of morphisms $\eta(x)\colon f(x)\rightarrow g(x)$ in $D_{1}$ for all $x\in C_{0}$ such that $\eta(x)\circ f(a)=g(a)\circ\eta(y)$ for any $a\in C_{1}(x,y)$, i.e. the following diagram commutes. $\xymatrix@R=10mm@C=10mm{f(x)\ar[r]^{\eta(x)}\ar[d]_{f(a)}&g(x)\ar[d]^{g(a)}\\ f(y)\ar[r]_{\eta(y)}&g(y)}$
Definition 3.26. [25] A crossed module over group-groupoids consist of group-groupoid morphisms $\alpha\colon\mathbb{G}\rightarrow\mathbb{H}$ and $\theta\colon\mathbb{H}\rightarrow\mathcal{A}(\mathbb{G})$, i.e. a group-groupoid action of $\mathbb{H}$ on $\mathbb{G}$, such that $\alpha_{1}\colon G_{1}\rightarrow H_{1}$ is a crossed module over groups.
Definition 3.4. [20] Let $\mathbb{G}$ be a group-groupoid and $\mathbb{H}$ a normal subgroup-groupoid of $\mathbb{G}$. Then the quotient group $G_{1}/N_{1}$ is a group-groupoid on the quotient group $G_{0}/N_{0}$. This group-groupoid is called the quotient group-groupoid and denoted by $\mathbb{G}/\mathbb{N}$.
Definition 3.23. A group-groupoid is called complete if $Z(\mathbb{G})=\bm{0}$ and the canonical morphism $\varphi\colon\mathbb{G}\rightarrow\mathcal{A}(\mathbb{G})$ is an isomorphism.
Definition 3.2. [20] Let $\mathbb{G}$ be a group-groupoid and $\mathbb{H}$ a subgroupoid of $\mathbb{G}$ such that $H_{1}$ is a subgroup of $G_{1}$. Then $\mathbb{H}$ is called a subgroup-groupoid of $\mathbb{G}$ and this denoted by $\mathbb{H}\leqslant\mathbb{G}$.
Definition 3.11. Let $\mathbb{G}$ be a group-groupoid. Then the group-groupoid $(\mathcal{W}(\mathbb{G}),\operatorname{Aut}(\mathbb{G}))$ defined above is called the actor group-groupoid of $\mathbb{G}$ and denoted by $\mathcal{A}(\mathbb{G})$.
Definition 3.28. The holomorph $\operatorname{Hol}(\mathbb{G})$ of a group-groupoid $\mathbb{G}$ is the semi-direct product group-groupoid $\mathbb{G}\rtimes\mathcal{A}(\mathbb{G})$ where the action $\theta\colon\mathcal{A}(\mathbb{G})\rightarrow\mathcal{A}(\mathbb{G})$ is the conjugation.
Definition 1.2. A non-unital $A_{\infty}$-structure on a graded vector space $A$ is a sequence of multilinear operations $\mu_{n}=\mu_{n}^{A}:A^{\otimes n}\to A,$ where $\deg(\mu_{n})=2-n,$ satisfying the following relations: $\sum\limits_{i+j+k=n+1}(-1)^{l_{1}^{i}(a)}\mu_{i+k+1}(a_{1},\dots,a_{i},\mu_{j% }(a_{i+1},\dots,a_{i+j}),a_{i+j+1},\dots,a_{n})=0,$ for $n\geq 0.$ Here for $1\leq p\leq q\leq n$ we put $l_{p}^{q}(a):=|a_{p}|+\dots+|a_{q}|+q-p+1.$
Definition 1.8. 1) A non-unital $A_{\infty}$-algebra $A$ is called strictly unital if there is a (unique) element $1=1_{A}\in A$ such that $\mu_{1}(1)=0,$ $\mu_{2}(1,a)=a=(-1)^{|a|}\mu_{2}(a,1)$ for any homogeneous element $a\in A,$ and for $n\geq 3$ we have $\mu_{n}(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})=0$ if at least one of the arguments $a_{i}$ equals $1.$ 2) A non-unital $A_{\infty}$-morphism $f:A\to B$ between strictly unital $A_{\infty}$-algebras is called strictly unital if $f_{1}(1_{A})=1_{B},$ and for $n\geq 2$ we have $f_{n}(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})=0$ if at least one of the arguments $a_{i}$ equals $1.$ 3) Given a strictly unital $A_{\infty}$-algebra $A,$ an $A_{\infty}$ $A$-module $M$ is called strictly unital if $\mu_{2}^{M}(m,1)=(-1)^{|m|+1}m,$ and for $n\geq 3$ we have $\mu_{n}^{M}(m,a_{1},\dots,a_{n-1})=0$ if at least one of $a_{i}$’s equals $1.$ 4) Given strictly unital $A_{\infty}$-algebras $A,$ $B,$ an $A_{\infty}$ $A-B$-bimodule is called strictly unital if $\mu_{1,0}^{M}(1_{A},m)=m,$ $\mu_{0,1}^{M}(m,1_{B})=(-1)^{|m|+1}m,$ and for $k+l\geq 2$ we have $\mu_{k,l}(a_{1},\dots,a_{k},m,b_{1},\dots,b_{l})=0$ if at least one of $a_{i}$’s equals $1_{A}$ or at least one of $b_{j}$’s equals $1_{B}.$
